Network Forensics > [T4]: Protocol Hierarchy

The "Protocol Hierarchy" window provides a comprehensive overview of the protocol distribution within the captured packets, presenting a tree-like structure of all the protocols in the capture. Each row in the window represents a protocol and displays various associated statistical values.

"Protocol Hierarchy" window - zoom in

Columns in the Protocol Hierarchy Window:

  • Protocol: The name of the protocol being analyzed.
    1. The first node in the tree typically includes Ethernet, as it is a commonly used protocol that encapsulates the whole packet.
    2. The subsequent node will indicate the version of Internet Protocol employed. As stated in the image, the version used is IPv4.
    3. The third node contains the protocol used on the Transport layer. In this example, the highlighted protocol is TCP.
    4. The bottom level of the protocol hierarchy focuses on the highly relevant protocols to users and potential attackers. It highlights protocols frequently targeted by attackers, including file-sharing protocols like SMB and RDP, as well as prominent attack vectors such as web protocols (XML) and email protocols (IMAP, POP). This aspect holds particular significance for analysts.
  • Percent Packets: The percentage of packets containing the specific protocol concerning all packets in the capture. For instance, by examining the percentage of packets and bytes attributed to each protocol, analysts identify that SMB protocol is rarely used in the environment. This finding may indicate malicious activities related to file sharing.
  • Packets: The total number of packets that include the protocol.
  • Percent Bytes: The percentage of bytes occupied by the protocol in relation to the total bytes in the capture.
  • Bytes: The total number of bytes attributed to the protocol.
  • Bits/s: The bandwidth utilization of the protocol relative to the capture time.
  • End Packets: The absolute number of packets where the protocol was the highest in the stack (last dissected).
  • End Bytes: The absolute number of bytes where the protocol was the highest in the stack (last dissected).
  • End Bits/s: The bandwidth utilization of the protocol relative to the capture time, considering when it was the highest protocol in the stack (last dissected).
  • PDUs: The total number of Protocol Data Units (PDUs) associated with the protocol.

Here are a couple of indicators you may check to spot anomalies over the network:

  1. Protocol Identification: For example, the Protocol Hierarchy window reveals that the captured network traffic consists of protocols such as HTTP, DNS, and FTP. This information helps analysts understand the types of protocols involved in the communication.

  2. Traffic Analysis: For instance, by examining the percentage of packets and bytes attributed to each protocol, analysts identify that a significant portion of the network traffic is related to the SSH protocol. This finding may indicate a high volume of secure remote access activities.

  3. Protocol Relationships: An example is when the Protocol Hierarchy window shows that HTTP is encapsulated within SSL/TLS. This insight reveals that the web traffic is encrypted and transmitted over a secure connection.

  4. Abnormal Protocol Behavior: Suppose the Protocol Hierarchy window displays a sudden increase in the percentage of ICMP packets compared to the baseline. This observation suggests a potential network anomaly or Denial of Service (DoS) attack.

  5. Protocol-specific Analysis: By focusing on a specific protocol, such as DNS, analysts can analyze the distribution of DNS query types (A, MX, PTR, etc.) within the captured traffic. This analysis can help identify any abnormal DNS behavior or potential DNS tunneling activities.
